[2] Togo
Date: Mon, 1 Mar 2004
From: Alfonso J. Rodriguez <arodriguezm@SaludFMV.org>
Source: Afrol News, Africa [edited]
<http://www.afrol.com/articles/11544>

More than 650 cholera cases in Togo
-------------------------------------
A cholera epidemic in the Togolese capital, Lome, has so far caused 661
cases and 37 deaths, according to the Togolese Red Cross. While the
epidemic is still on the increase, the Red Cross is heading information and
awareness work to prevent a greater disaster in the city of 700 000
inhabitants.
The Togolese Red Cross Society reports from Lome that it is now supporting
an urgent collaborative response to the cholera epidemic in the Togolese
capital city. While 37 Lome citizens have already died from cholera, there
are reports that the epidemic is still increasing.
At a meeting a month ago, the Togolese Red Cross had agreed to mobilise and
train a further 150 volunteers to respond to the epidemic. The response to
the Lome epidemic is headed by the Togolese Ministry of Health and the
World Health Organisation (WHO).
According to the Togolese Red Cross, its volunteers have by now visited
some 1250 households in the affected region and reached more than 20 000
people with "information and education on prevention and management."
Together with local health authorities and the WHO, Red Cross volunteers
are now conducting a mass awareness campaigns through radio and public
institutions such as schools. Other activities to control the spread of the
epidemic include active case surveillance and referring infected persons to
special clinics established to treat cholera patients.
There is fear of the epidemic escalating as the rains are increasing, the
Togolese Red Cross says. The organization has therefore requested more
support for a more effective intervention.
******
[3] Mozambique
Date: Tue, 23 Mar 2004
From: Marianne Hopp <mjhopp12@yahoo.com>
Source: WHO Disease Outbreak [edited]
<http://www.who.int/csr/don/2004_03_23/en/>

Cholera in Mozambique
--------------------------
The Ministry of Health of Mozambique has reported a total of 15 237 cases
and 85 deaths between 20 Dec 2003 and 18 Mar 2004 in 7 provinces (Maputo,
Gaza, Sofala, Zambesia, Nampula, Inhambane, and Tete). Maputo city is the
worst-affected area with 9522 cases and 37 deaths.
A cholera emergency was declared by the Ministry of Health on 9 Jan 2004.
WHO and other agencies, including UNICEF, Medecins sans Frontieres, World
Food Programme, the United States Agency for International Development
(USAID), and the Italian Government are supporting local health authorities
in containing the outbreak.
******
[4] South Africa (Eastern Cape)
Date: Wed, 24 Mar 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: SABC news [edited]
<http://www.sabcnews.com/south_africa/health/0,2172,76536,00.html>

Cholera confirmed as killer of 13 in Transkei
---------------------------------------------
13 people in the Eastern Cape have died from cholera and more than 100 had
to be treated in hospital for the disease after a recent outbreak. The
provincial government has promised the affected communities emergency
medical resources to stop the spread of the disease.
Monwabisi Goqwana, the health MEC, yesterday flew to Sebeni in Ntabankulu,
one of 3 affected villages, to confirm the outbreak. Goqwana appealed to
the community not to blame the deaths on witchcraft.
During 2003, the Eastern Cape health department delivered 200 water tanks
to the areas around Qumbu to address the cholera problem. Cholera strains
usually plague the area once summer rains start. The disease has claimed
many lives over the past 3 years in rural Transkei, due to a lack of clean
water and sanitation.
Meanwhile, the Japanese government has provided an additional R37 million
[USD 5.6 million] for a water supply project in the Eastern Cape. A total
of R71 million [USD 10.8 million] has now been invested in the
project. The project has thus far provided water to 13 communities in the
Eastern Cape, and 8 more will now benefit.
The money will be spent on water pipes and 12 new wells.
