[5] Zambia
Date: Sat, 27 Mar 2004 11:56:22 -0400
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <arodriguezm@SaludFMV.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200403290278.html>

Cholera Hits State Lodge
-----------------------
Cholera has broken out at State Lodge in Lusaka, with 4 people currently
undergoing treatment at various cholera centers. Acting assistant for
press and public relations at State House, Jack Kalala, confirmed the
outbreak at the police camp, housing staff and families of presidential
security staff at the presidential lodge, although the situation had been
contained. The affected are mainly police officers and their families.
He said 16 people were discharged yesterday and there were no deaths
reported. He dismissed assertions that a child had died in the camp,
saying the child who had died lived near the affected area and was being
treated in the house for cholera, where she died. Kalala said the cause of
the outbreak was due to a sewer pipe that burst and contaminated the
drinking water in the police camp. He said the pipe is currently being
worked on by the Ministry of Works and Supply.
Kalala said the camp was now being serviced by the Zambia National Service
(ZNS), who were providing safe water. He said the Minister of Health Dr.
Brian Chituwo had since been to State Lodge to assess the situation, which
he found to be stable. He said cholera cases had reduced to a manageable
level.
According to a source who declined to be named, there were 71 initial
cholera patients as of Tuesday at the cholera centers.
